Well the 6,000 buried is a conjecture. Scud missiles managed to take out a
few dozen American lives. The gassing of the Iranians in the face of a
massive upset during their human wave attacks was in fact protested
officially in the U.N and stateside. 50% children is accurate. It's also
none of our concern. The Iraqi people have brought this upon themselves in
the same way that the German people brought about their own destruction in
WWII or more recently in Czechoslovakia.

Infatuation and herdlike submission to a personality cult leader (no matter
how gruesome his repressive tactics are) is tantamount to cowardice. The
world has changed, and the old excuses from idealistic doe-eyed citizens
flailing helplessly as their taxes and wealth fund atrocity don't cut it
anymore.

And just where are the dissenters in Iraq? They're huddled beneath no-fly
zones. Or ripping off the U.N.'s aid packages. Or worse, they've exported
their brains and con-men (don't underestimate the importance of con-men to
revolution) west to Britian and Wall Street with stops along the way to rip
off Syrian Banks and drum up Egyptian and Palestinian support (great
company). In the vacuum, the apologists and masses have created a fetid,
apathetic breeding ground for this _butchery_.

But, when it's done, we'll spend billions on medication, food, and
rebuilding. Like we have for the past 12 years through oil for food and
medicine programs, defending the Kurds in the North, and the Saudi's, and
Kuwait.

America has blood on her hands and her fangs. This is true. None of us is
proud of this. Who else is going to enforce peace? Without action, 12
years from now, after the French and Russians have retooled the Republican
guard, what would prevent Saddam or his sons from marching out again on
another fool's errand. (&quot;winning&quot; the war with Iran basically meant that
Iraq got to maintain it's pre-war boundaries after sustaining massive
personnel and infrastructure losses; we all know what happened when they
&quot;annexed&quot; Kuwait) Would a radioactive, scorched-earth Iraq, after they
naively dump sarin gas or small nuke in downtown Tel Aviv and find
themselves on the business end of the 20+ large strategic Nukes, and hundred
plus battlefield/tacticle projectiles make you happy - would it fulfil your
principles for good international governance.

Humans kill one another. That's what we do. That's what we'll always do.
We try to moderate it. Sometimes we're successful; sometimes we're not. In
this case there were multiple failures on both sides and through
international entities. People are going to die. Not innocent people.
Just people.
So take your statistics and your thin veneer of self-righteousness, stuff
them in your mouth and swallow. You'll find them to be singularly
uncomfortable and indigestible.

</POST>



